items.name: Snow White
items.description:
Please contact me here on civitAi or on Twitter if you want to provide the LoRa in a generation service.

TLDR (Because I don't care)

Use snow white <lora:snowWhite_v10:1> in positiv promt.

If you like the LoRa, please feel free to share your generated images here and leave a review (or at least a rating) ;D

About

I still enjoy making models for animated stuff, especially this old stuff is challenging.

The last time I watched Snow White was ages ago (back when VHS was still a thing) and I never realised how "badly" made it was compared to more modern films, but it's actually from 1937 so I give them a bit of slack (it's actually quite good when you think about it, it was the first "long" animated film ever as far as I know).

I never noticed that Snow White had her eyes closed for most of the film (and to be honest, when she did open her eyes, she had some really crazy eyes, at the time, drawing eyes wasn't their forte, but they definitely got better. About 13 years later, with the release of Cinderella, they actually learned how to make eyes that were not scary :D (Which is another LoRa in the making, by the way ^^)

Training

Well, like I said, I tried to only use frames where she had her eyes open, so I worked with 36 images for training.

This approach increased a small problem: there are not many pictures where her skirt is involved, so look in the next section how to prevent her from going full comando on your pictures (or at least without a skirt xD). And this time I calculated the learning rate properly instead of eyeballing the values.

Usage

There is no need to adjust the weight - it's as simple as that:

snow white <lora:snowWhite_v10:1>

I suggest adding long skirt f you want to have her completely in her famous dress, otherwise she will be bottomless most of the time...

items.name: Karahara Shima - ÂîêÂéüÂøóÈ∫ª
items.description:
Simple LORA trained on art of an original character of artist Kotoba Noriaki. The model is supposed to generate (with varying success) Karahara Shima, a gloomy girl with burns across the left half of her face and torso.

This is my first attempt at training a LORA so I will definitely try and improve on this once I get a better grip on training.

v1 Release

This model works reasonably well (I think). Only requires the listed activation tag and works best at a weight between 0.8-1.0 (try using 1.0 in most cases, but consider going down to 0.8 if there is some bad interaction with another LORA, which should hopefully be rare).

The burn scars (at least for a weight of 1.0) should work reasonably well now, but if they don't just add another "burn scars" into the prompt (and play around with the tag weight until it looks nice).

modelVersions.name: v1
modelVersions.description:
I turned down the LORA network dimension to 4 (with an alpha of 2), which seems to have improved the quality of results pretty well.

Results are now fairly consistent with much less need to specify characteristics. However the burn marks may still be somewhat finicky, try adding "burn scars" to your tags and experiment with weights until you like the results. Location of the marks is semi-consistent.

Training info: 7 epochs on 29 images with 10 repetitions each. Learning rate of 5e-4.
I trained a total of 10 epochs, but the later ones would yield worse results presumably due to overcooking.

modelVersions.name: v0.2
modelVersions.description:
Preliminary version, may be somewhat wonky. General features seem to be replicated relatively well but may need some nudging in the right direction. Adding an additional "burn scars" seems to help bring out the burns a bit better.

Works reasonably well on all of the models I've tested and should work decent-ish with other LORAs (although I've mostly only played around with styles so far).

Trained on a set of 29 images that were extracted from various sources (Gelbooru, Twitter, pixiv) and lightly edited to get rid of easy to remove artifacts such as signatures, text and speech bubbles.
Most of the images I used are in a standing pose, either from a cowboy or upper body shot. This seems to be reflected in the default pose of the generated images, but other poses should still be doable.

Training was done for 10 epochs and 10 repeats each with a batch size of 2, an input resolution of 512x512 and a network dimension of 16 (and consequently an alpha of 8).

There are some other images that I might still absorb into the training set that may require some additional clean up to improve results. I've trained a prior version with the same training data but a higher network dimension, which turned out somewhat worse (presumably due to overfitting on the small sample size).

Other than increasing the sample count I'd also like to try training at a higher resolution next.

items.name: Full Feature Character Prompts - Fantasy
items.description:
80+ detailed dynamic prompts with fantasy, sci-fi, video game, mythological and historical themes. Each prompt includes setting, background, pose and (mostly) gender-agnostic character details.

Now introducing the lite version of the wildcards: the same wildcards, without the LoRas in them. There is still plenty of variance among generated images even without the LoRas, but expect less overall flavor when using the lite version.
The lite version is useful

  • if you want to run batch generations, as the without the LoRas, there won't be cross-contamination aming the images in the batch

  • if you don't want to download the ever increasing list of LoRas

  • if you want to rely more on the base model, without LoRas potentially influencing the style of the generation

Note: textual inversions (embeddings) are still utilized in the lite version, so please download the ones listed below.

Usage:

Add a description of the character you'd like in the generated image (feel free to use character LoRas), plus any style/quality keywords necessary for the model you're using, then add __full-prompt-fantasy__ to the prompt.

Example:
best quality, masterpiece, 1man, russian (male:1.1), solo, aquamarine eyes, long brown beard, __full-prompt-fantasy__

Some example characters are provided in the character.txt in the downloaded archive, so if you just want to run a few tests, you can use the following prompt:
best quality, masterpiece, __character__ __full-prompt-fantasy__

More diverse character wildcards can be found here: https://civitai.com/models/118508?modelVersionId=128565

Negative prompt should be whatever the model necessitates, or your preferred negative prompt. Some models have race or gender bias due to the material that was used for training, you can usually use negative prompts to compensate. eg. if your generations come out with female characters despite describing the character as male, add "woman, girl" to the negative prompt, use weights if necessary.

Other settings mostly depend on the model, use whatever gives good results even without the wildcards. Image aspect ratio should either be portrait, or 1:1 (most test-generations were made with 512x768 resolution).

Additional usage notes:

Other than the above, feel free to experiment with additions to the prompt, though most of the wildcards are rather long, so if you want to have a significant impact, weights may be necessary. The prompts rarely use weights above 1.1, so if your additions seem to have no effect, try weights of 1.15 or more.

Important notes:

Necessary extensions:

  • https://github.com/adieyal/sd-dynamic-prompts (needed for wildcards to work)

  • https://github.com/KohakuBlueleaf/a1111-sd-webui-lycoris (needed for LyCORIS models to work)

If you are upgrading from a previous version:

  • Orange color means that the model name changed since previous version, please rename your file/download the latest version before using the wildcards.

  • Green color means that the model was added since previous version, please download these before using the wildcards.

FIRST 4/25/23

Lemme take u in deep short backstory of my inspiration

Blue Moonü•∞ from Cyberpunk 2077 the breathtaking character as game as well.

When had i first heard and learnt about US CRACKS..... oy boy(long sigh). I instantly wanted to meet them in the game (ngl i love every single quest that i completed). And eventually i have been taken a chance to meet them that was abrupt+awesome (as now remembering *incoming call Kerry*

Kerry: drop whatever u doin' meet me at the marina, don't make me wait )more spoilers ahead so u better play it by yourself)

Well...(these warm memories still chasing me) lemme tell u of model a little bit.

Fist thing first all the data that i could scrap and i did were game engine screenshots(intensively waving to the nsfw enjoyers) made by me+from net.

(do not frustrating now there's always is a solution see about that version and +nsfw capabilities also depends of models)

Second as per of data lack this training was a challenge one (as any other train in kohya-ss). I've spent literally a whole(~26h.) day only on trainings (in the name of science i suppose...yeah)
